{"questionId":"22193","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A particle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> moves along the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis. The velocity of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> at time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds,&nbsp;where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>3</mn></math>. When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>P</mi></math> is at the origin <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Sketch a graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math> against <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>, clearly showing any points of intersection&nbsp;with the axes.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><img src=\"__IMG__/901ffa8fdd9b9184a1bd11bec30a385de2cfd783.png\"></p>\n<p>valid approach to solve&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(may be seen in part (a))&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>±</mo><msqrt><mn>16</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>48</mn></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>correct <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>- intercept on the graph at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> The following two <em><strong>A</strong></em> marks may only be awarded if the shape is a&nbsp;concave down parabola. These two marks are independent of each&nbsp;other and the <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em>.</p>\n<p><br>correct domain from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> starting at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> must be clearly indicated.</p>\n<p><br>vertex in approximately correct place for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4</strong></em><em><strong>&nbsp;marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22193","referenceCode":"21N.1.SL.TZ0.7b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Sketch a graph of v against t, clearly showing any points of intersection with the axes.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between curve and x axis","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.9—Kinematics problems","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Quadratic function"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}